<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[264,1324,1791,1897]" lastBlockId="8.[264,1323,284,390]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis box="[264,366,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Remarks</emphasis>
. —This species is known from only one record off 
<collectingCountry box="[981,1049,1791,1817]" name="Chile" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Chile</collectingCountry>
: 
<geoCoordinate box="[1061,1155,1791,1817]" degrees="47" direction="south" minutes="01" orientation="latitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" precision="925" value="-47.016666">47°01'S</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1168,1271,1791,1817]" degrees="75" direction="west" minutes="44" orientation="longitude" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" precision="925" value="-75.73333">75°44'W</geoCoordinate>
(off Península Tres Montes) at 
<quantity box="[594,688,1831,1857]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.146" pageId="7" pageNumber="22" unit="m" value="1146.0">1146 m</quantity>
, although additional specimens are known from off southern South America from Rio Grande, 
<collectingCountry box="[769,841,1871,1897]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Brazil</collectingCountry>
to Cabo Tres Puntas, 
<collectingCountry box="[1096,1213,1871,1897]" name="Argentina" pageId="7" pageNumber="22">Argentina</collectingCountry>
at depths of 
<quantity box="[295,442,284,310]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.75" metricValueMax="12.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" unit="m" value="875.0" valueMax="1250.0" valueMin="500.0">500–1250 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cairns, S. D." box="[456,604,284,310]" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" refId="ref14291" refString="Cairns, S. D. (1982) Antarctic and Subantarctic Scleractinia. Antarctic Research Series, 34 (1), 74 pp., 18 pls., 14 maps." type="book" year="1982">Cairns 1982</bibRefCitation>
). It is characterized as having a colony with large (up to 
<quantity box="[1265,1323,284,310]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="23" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
in CD) sympodially arranged corallites, a fascicular columella, four cycles of septa and one crown of 12 P3, and occasionally intratentacular budding.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
